description:
The spec for MaxTimeMS in drivers says that drivers *may* implement MaxTimeMS for {{find_one}}.  This was not done for the perl driver.  We could add another parameter for cursor options like this:

{code}
$coll->find_one( $query, $fields, { max_time_ms => 100 } );
{code}

I use 20 perl processes for query a collection concurrently. For example:
    my $Node_Coll = $db->get_collection( 'Node' );
    #$id is different in different processes.
    my $object = $Node_Coll->find_one({ “_id” => $id },
    {"AdminIP"  => 1,"community" => 1,"port" => 1,"version" => 1}
    );

The result is below:
query condition:  54279dc9945700a4da3128b0
result:           '_id' => bless( {
                          'value' => '54279dc9945700a4da3128b1'
                        }, 'MongoDB::OID' ),
query condition:  54279dc9945700a4da3128b1
result:          '_id' => bless( {
                          'value' => '54279dc9945700a4da3128b0'
                        }, 'MongoDB::OID' ),
query condition:   54279dc9945700a4da3128af
result:          '_id' => bless( {
                          'value' => '54279dc9945700a4da3128af'
                        }, 'MongoDB::OID' ),

Some results is right, some results is wrong. It's confuse.

I use 50ms sleep, all of result is right. So I think it maybe exists race condition in perl driver.
